  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 3:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ποιήσατε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "produce",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καρπὸν ἄξιον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "worthy fruit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Orige[122] remarks, that in St Matthew worthy fruit is required in the singular number from the Pharisees and Sadducees; whereas, in St Luke, worthy fruits are required in the plural number from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the people",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". I do not myself see what difference it makes in the matter. The singular ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καρπὸς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fruit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is often used collectively; and in the preaching of St John it may be opposed to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "barrenness:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the plural number, it implies ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fecundity",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Men are here represented as trees; and the fruit is, therefore, their repentance.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τῆς μετανοίας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "of repentance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Construe these words with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καρπὸν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".[123] Thus, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 26:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", we read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἄξια τῆς μετανοὶας ἔργα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μετάνοια",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "repentance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is an entire change of character,[124] and a renunciation of all that is evil, by which renunciation we wish that evil void or undone.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[122] rigen (born about 186 A.D., died 253 A.D., a Greek father: two-thirds of the N. Test. are quoted in his writings). Ed. Vinc. Delarue, Paris. 1733, 1740, 1759.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[123] Bengel would apparently render the passage thus: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "worthy fruit of repentance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and so in the passage immediately cited from the Acts, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "worthy works of repentance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". E. V. has, in the one passage, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fruits meet for repentance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; in the other, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "works meet for repentance.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—(I. B.)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[124] This scarcely expresses the original “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "transmutatio mentis",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".” Ainsworth gives us the first signification of MENS—“",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "That part of the rational soul which is the seat of natural parts and acquired virtues",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".”—(I. B.)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Bring forth therefore",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "vide supra",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "fruits",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "fruit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Revised Version). The plural is due to a false reading taken from the parallel passage of Luke - it regards the various graces of a good life as so many different fruits (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 21:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); the singular, as one product from one source (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Galatians 5:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The term used here (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ποιεῖν καρπόν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and frequently, lays more stress on the effort involved than ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "διδόναι καρπόν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", simple \"yielding\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 8:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "φέρειν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"bearing\" in the course of nature (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 7:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 15:4, 5, 8, 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The preacher requires a repentance which produces results. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Meet for",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 26:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Though strictly meaning \"suitable to\" (\"answering to,\" Authorized Version margin; cf. Tyndale, 'be-longyng to\"), the phrase might to-day be understood as \"suitable to produce.\" John really means that true repentance has fruit which belongs to its proper nature, and which is alone \"worthy of\" it (Revised Version). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Repentance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τῆς μετανοίας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The article is either generic (Authorized Version and Revised Version; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 11:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and probably Acts 26:20); or equivalent to \"your\" (Revised Version margin). If the latter, the following sentence shows that it is still said in good faith. (For repentance, cf. ver. 1, note.) Matthew 3:8",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]